<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="62736" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="62736">Diagnosis</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="62736">
(
<bibRefCitation author="Oliveira, Lejeune P. H." journalOrPublisher="Boletim do Instituto Paulista de Oceanografia" pageId="0" pageNumber="62736" pagination="3 - 34" refId="B6840577" refString="Oliveira, Lejeune P. H., 1951. The genus Elasmopus on the coast of Brazil with description of Elasmopus besnardi n. sp., and E. fusimanus n. sp. (Crustacea, Amphipoda). Boletim do Instituto Paulista de Oceanografia 2 (2): 3 - 34" title="The genus Elasmopus on the coast of Brazil with description of Elasmopus besnardi n. sp., and E. fusimanus n. sp. (Crustacea, Amphipoda)" volume="2" year="1951">Oliveira 1951</bibRefCitation>
): Dark dorsum. Head with two ellipsoid eyes, twice longer than large, located close to lobe between both antennae. Pereopod coxae 1-4 of similar length and almost twice the size of the 5-7 ones (5th with an anterior lobe wider than posterior). First pairs of antennae longer than second ones (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStartId="F6448414" pageId="0" pageNumber="62736">9</figureCitation>
<figureCitation captionStartId="F6448420" pageId="0" pageNumber="62736">b</figureCitation>
). First pair of gnathopods longer than second ones. Males telson similarly longer than wide, with a median cleft to about 2/3 of its length; in females, cleft close to base and as long as broad.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
